## First-time Setup

`start.sh` bootstraps everything on first run:

- Clones the upstream platform into `stellars-jupyterhub-ds/` (a plain clone listed in `.gitignore`, **not** a git submodule, treated as read-only)
- Generates a self-signed TLS cert into `certs/` if none is present, sourcing `CERTS_CN` and `CERTS_DNS_ALTNAMES` from `certs/certs.params` (rendered from your copier answers)
- Pulls images and starts the stack

Just run:

```bash
./start.sh
```

To regenerate the cert manually:

```bash
# Use the rendered defaults in certs/certs.params (edit it first if you want different values)
bash certs/certs_generate.sh

# Or override on the command line for a one-off
bash certs/certs_generate.sh --cn "Custom CN" --dns-altnames "x.example.com,*.example.com"
```

If you change `CERTS_DNS_ALTNAMES`, the new cert/key pair goes into a new `certs/<new-prefix>/` directory (prefix is derived from the first altname, with `*` replaced by `_`). The fixed `certs/tls.yml` is overwritten in place. Delete the stale `certs/<old-prefix>/` directory if you want to clean up.

To install the generated cert into your OS trust store (so browsers stop warning), use the standalone helper that ships alongside the template:

```bash
# Linux / macOS - from a clone of the template repo
./extra/certs-installer/install_cert.sh /path/to/my-jupyterhub/certs/<prefix>/cert.pem

# Windows
extra\certs-installer\install_cert.bat C:\path\to\my-jupyterhub\certs\<prefix>\cert.pem
```

The helpers live in [copier-stellars-jupyterhub-ds/extra/certs-installer](https://github.com/stellarshenson/copier-stellars-jupyterhub-ds/tree/main/extra/certs-installer) and are intentionally not copied into the deployment.

## Deployment

```bash
./start.sh           # Start the stack
./start.sh --refresh # Pull latest upstream stellars-jupyterhub-ds + docker images
./stop.sh            # Stop all services
```

## Update from template

This deployment was generated by the [copier-stellars-jupyterhub-ds](https://github.com/stellarshenson/copier-stellars-jupyterhub-ds) Copier template. The interview answers are persisted in `.copier-answers.yml`. **Commit that file to your overlay repo** — `copier update` reads it to know which template version this deployment came from and replays your answers without re-asking.

```bash
copier update --trust
```

`--trust` lets copier run the template's `_tasks` (chmod on `start.sh` / `stop.sh`, plus the eager cert generation guard).

## First Admin Bootstrap

The first admin user is created in one of two modes. Both honour `JUPYTERHUB_ADMIN={{ admin_username }}` and never auto-create the admin with an unrecoverable random password.

**Self-signup (default)** - leave `JUPYTERHUB_ADMIN_PASSWORD` unset. On a fresh deployment with empty database, the signup form is silently re-opened scoped to `{{ admin_username }}` only. Visit `https://{% if jupyterhub_subdomain %}{{ jupyterhub_subdomain }}.{% endif %}{{ base_hostname }}/hub/signup`, register as `{{ admin_username }}` with a password you choose, and log in. NativeAuthenticator self-approves that signup and the admin role is granted at login. Any other username on the signup form is rejected. Once the admin exists in the database, the bootstrap window closes.

**Provisioned** - set `JUPYTERHUB_ADMIN_PASSWORD` in `compose_override.yml`:

```yaml
- JUPYTERHUB_ADMIN_PASSWORD=<your-initial-password>
```

The hub seeds the admin record with that password on startup. The value is **initial only** - once the admin changes their password through the UI, the env value is permanently ignored.

## Branding

The `branding/` directory is mounted read-only at `/srv/branding` in the JupyterHub container. The compose override sets:

- `JUPYTERHUB_LOGO_URI=file:///srv/branding/{{ branding_prefix }}_logo.png` - login page lockup
- `JUPYTERHUB_FAVICON_URI=file:///srv/branding/{{ branding_prefix }}_favicon.ico` - browser tab
- `JUPYTERHUB_LAB_MAIN_ICON_URI=file:///srv/branding/{{ branding_prefix }}_main_icon.svg` - JupyterLab top bar
- `JUPYTERLAB_SYSTEM_NAME={{ project_name }}` - displayed system name

To rebrand: drop replacement files at the same paths.

